  • Method Details

    • mainWrite

      public void mainWrite​(ItemProgramNode toWrite, java.lang.String fileName)
      mainWrite is essentially the 'main' method of the WriteOut class and is used to make ordered calls to the other writing and file generation methods.
      Parameters:
      toWrite - is the tree of pantry items that the user has loaded into the application and edited.
      fileName - is what the user would like the output file to be named. This implementation must use unique file names as it cannot overwrite.

    • createNew

      public java.io.File createNew​(java.lang.String fileName)
      createNew is a helper method used for generating user specific output files for the purpose of writing the ItemProgramNode tree out to a new file.
      Parameters:
      fileName - is what the user would like the output file to be named. This implementation must use unique file names as it cannot overwrite.
      Returns:
      the file to be used by other methods in this class, OR null if an error was flagged at any point.

    • writer

      public void writer​(java.io.File dest, ItemProgramNode src, java.lang.String fileName)
      writer is the core method in creating output files. Using the filename specified by the user, this method takes the ItemProgramNode found in src and outputs it to the dest file.
      Parameters:
      dest - is the created file that we are writing src out to.
      src - is the ItemProgramNode to write to the file.
      fileName - is what the user would like the output file to be named. This implementation must use unique file names as it cannot overwrite.

    • getErrorCode

      public java.lang.String getErrorCode()
      getErrorCode is a getter method for determining the point at which the writer failed EARLIEST.
      Returns:
      "nE" - no Error; "fAE" - file name already exists; "fC" - file creation error; "fNF" - file not found error. Further error codes are not thrown by WriteOut.class and are instead generated during the validation step. For these error codes, see Parser.getErrorCode()
